Fiber photometry measures aggregate fluorescence signals from a population of neurons through a single optical fiber. Unlike calcium imaging with a Miniscope, it does not provide single-cell resolution, but it is simpler to implement and can record from multiple brain regions simultaneously using multi-fiber setups.

== Typical Setup ==
* An optical fiber is implanted above the target brain region
* Excitation light is delivered through the fiber
* Emitted fluorescence travels back through the same fiber to a photodetector
* Signal reflects the summed activity of all labeled neurons in the field of view

== Use Cases ==
* Monitoring activity in genetically defined cell populations during behavior
* Multi-region recordings with low surgical complexity
* Experiments where single-cell resolution is not required
